Introduction

The idea behind this project was to see if the happiness ranking of a country as given by the 2017 Gallup poll was reflected in the happiness of the major literary works from that country. I used three data sources to do this; Wikipedia, R-Gutenberg package, and the Gallup 2017 Happiness poll data.

First I decided to look at overall happiness trends throughout the world. Then I zeroed in on 5 countries in particular; Russia, Greece, France, USA and the UK and explored the happiness trends in those countries. The reason I chose these countries, is the R-Gutenberg package mainly contains Western authors. I would have been very interested to do a East vs West analysis of literary and happiness trends, but unfortunately the Gutenberg package doesnt contain many Eastern authors.

Above we see that most of the high-ranking countries are either in Europe or Australia while the low-ranking countries are in Africa. The top countries and lowest ranked countries also differ in what variables they consider important to their happiness.

Happiness Variable Contribution by Ranking

Here we see that the top 10 countries seem to have a consensus on what makes them happy. GDP and Family are both most important followed by Health, Freedom, Generosity and Government Corruption.

The bottom 10 countries have much less consensus on what makes them happy. They all do seem to value Family however.

Happiness by Region

The average happiness by world region is not too surprising. Overall, more developed regions seem to report happier citizens.

Happiness Variables by World Region

There do appear to be some differences in what each world region considers most important to their happiness. In North America and Western Europe, GDP seems to be most important in determining happiness. However, in all the other regions, Family ranks higher than GDP. This is most visible in Sub-Saharan AFrica, Asia and the Latin American regions.

Method

For each of the five countries examined I scraped the Wikipedia pages of 20-30 of its most prominent authors. I then scored the pages using the AFINN lexicon for its positive vs negative sentiment. I reasoned authors with more negative biographies, probably led unhappier lives. Conversely, those with more positive biographies led happier lives. I assigned each author a Mean Bio Score

I then used the R-Gutenberg package to score the major literary works of these authors using both the AFINN and NRC lexicons and assigned each author a Mean Book Score for the overall positivity/negativity of their body of work.

Finally, I joined the Mean Bio Scores, Mean Book Scores and NRC Scores on author into one large table. The table required some light regex cleaning to deal with the accents in some of the authors name.

The NRC lexicon was used to find the proportion of words used by each author corresponding to emotions like joy and fear.

The AFINN lexicon was used since it applies a score to words ranging from -5 to 5. I found this lexicon more nuanced than the BING lexicon which simply categorizes words into 1 or -1 scores. For example, with BING, the phrase tortured and exiled would receive the same negative score as unhappy and sad childhood which I didnt think was adequate.

Literary Analysis

Now we can look at some plots and see if there are any relationships between the happiness of an author, and the overall sentiment of their work. We will also examine whether an authors native countrys happiness is related to their own happiness, as well as the overall sentiment of their work.

Here I plotted the authors happiness against the sentiment scores of their books. I was hoping to see a linear relationship, that happier authors write happier books. But for the most part, this does not seem to be the case, with a large cluster of the authors hovering around the 0 score on both book sentiment and biography sentiment.

NRC Analysis

Now I examine how each country and the authors from those countries differed in their use of NRC words like joy, surprise, anger etc. I had hoped for a pattern to emerge, like American authors used more pride word on average than other countries. However, what emerged was the fact that the proportion of NRC emotion words used by each country was about the same.

To perform these analyses, I had to gather the NRC variables in my authors_and_bios table in order to be able to plot them all together.
